data.jamchart_notes: This sludge-y riff rock monster of a Rockdale is the first truly extended venture for the song and features elements of That's All (Genesis), Peter absolutely wailing on clav & vibes, and a Dragonfly-esque progression to bring it all home.

data.jamchart_notes: Jam flows magically with so much purpose, from methodical funk to beautiful blissful bring down to glorious climbing march to experimenting with darkness to rocking finish. Great improv with diverse jamming themes.

data.jamchart_notes: A wicked parade that meanders through a demented circus and the island of misfit toys before things start to get truly weird. data.jamchart_notes: At a svelte 15 minutes, one of the year’s most satisfying and efficient performances. Out of the verses, it drops immediately into a patient half-time jam undergirded by sultry organ and Big T funk. Channeling David Gilmour, Rick fills space with the fewest possible notes, crafting an ethereal soundscape. Lead guitar takes to the fore with a bluesy jam that dissolves into a brief Rush-like prog passage before building to a  satisfying tension-and-release peak.

data.jamchart_notes: The moment where the "short jam" clicked for Goose. Coming off of the incredible "+14 Minute Jam," the band gets spacey in the initial funk zone before a BEAUTIFUL transition into a bed of piano-dominated major mode. Builds back into the ending peak from there with nary a wasted second.

data.jamchart_notes: One of the few “Rockdales” to exceed 20 minutes, this version echoes (almost note-for-note) the circular, melodic, and triumphant force of the 9/7/24 SPAC “Drive,” centering around a repeating earworm that Rick gradually develops. Peter and Trevor support with a steady mid-tempo groove, leaving just enough space for some of Cotter’s most dynamic playing — simultaneously accenting and propelling the jam.

data.jamchart_notes: Gorgeous segue -> from "A Western Sun." Traverses an incredibly deep terrain for its relatively short 14-minute runtime. The jam grows heavy and punishing, the band taking their time as they work their way into evil territory. Coming up for air, things percolate for a bit before a relatively smooth transition into "Atlas Dogs."
